article.description: Sue Bird had 17 points, including five free throws in the final 54.1 seconds, and 10 assists as the Seattle Storm defeated the Los Angeles Sparks 81-76 on Thursday night.
article.headline: Storm creep closer to playoff berth
article.linkText: Storm send Sparks to second straight defeat
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sue Bird had 17 points, including five free
throws in the final 54.1 seconds, and 10 assists as the Seattle
Storm defeated the Los Angeles Sparks 81-76 on Thursday night.

	   Lauren Jackson added 19 points, and Kamila Vodichkova had 14 of
her 18 points and seven of her 10 rebounds in the second half for
the Storm (15-13), who beat the defending champions to extend their
franchise-record winning streak to five games.

	   "They are one of the finest teams in the WNBA,'' Seattle coach
Lin Dunn said. "Today is a tremendous day for the Seattle Storm.''

	   Lisa Leslie scored 20 of her season-high 30 points in the first
half and had a game-high 16 rebounds for Los Angeles (20-6).

	   The Sparks lost back-to-back games for the first time this
season, and it was the first time they lost consecutive home games
since July 1998.

	   "To lose two in a row is definitely unfamiliar territory,''
Leslie said. "Teams are playing hard and we've got to find a way
to stay mentally tough and focused for 40 minutes.''

	   Mwadi Mabika added 16 points before fouling out with 5.8 seconds
to play, and DeLisha Milton had 11 for the Sparks.

	   Leslie's basket with 2:09 remaining pulled Los Angeles to 74-73,
but Bird made two free throws with 54.1 seconds left to make it
76-73. Mabika missed a 3-point attempt 12 seconds later, but Bird
making two more free throws with 36.1 seconds left.

	   The Sparks' last chance to tie ended with Tamecka Dixon missing
a 3-point attempt with 8 seconds remaining.

	   Jackson sealed the victory by making two free throws with 5.8
seconds left.

	   "We had control of the game and we were just trying to take
time off the clock,'' Bird said. "We had a good lead and we knew
that if we played good defense and knocked down our foul shots, we
would get the win.''

	   The victory moved the Storm within a half-game of idle Portland
in the race for the Western Conference's fourth and final playoff
berth. Seattle has four games remaining.
